%md

### 2.2 Distribution of events

First, we will analize if students that dropout interact with the platform in a different way, by looking at the types of events most accessed. We want to compare what proportion of actions are of type X, separated by both groups.

Each course must be analized individually. To make this process simpler, we create an interactive visualization using Angular's backend and frontend APIs for Zeppelin.

msg.data:
2.2 Distribution of events

First, we will analize if students that dropout interact with the platform in a different way, by looking at the types of events most accessed. We want to compare what proportion of actions are of type X, separated by both groups.

Each course must be analized individually. To make this process simpler, we create an interactive visualization using Angular’s backend and frontend APIs for Zeppelin.

paragraphs.text:
val eventCounts = trainLogsDF
    .groupBy("course_id", "event", "enrollment_id").count()
    .join(trainEnrollmentDF.select("enrollment_id", "label"),
          Seq("enrollment_id"))
    .groupBy("event", "label", "course_id").count()

val totalCounts = eventCounts.groupBy("label", "course_id")
    .sum("count")
val eventRatios = eventCounts
    .join(totalCounts, Seq("label", "course_id"))
    .withColumn("eventRatio", $"count"/$"sum(count)")

eventRatios.registerTempTable("trainLogsDF")
eventRatios.cache()  // We cached it to get faster access for the interactive visualization

paragraphs.text:
%md

With the previous visualization, we observe in several courses that the proportion of `access` and `navigate` actions are more prominent on students who drop out. On the other hand, the events of type `problem` are more common in students who don't drop out. To verify this phenomena exists in all courses, we will create a more extensive visualization.

For both student groups, with and without dropout, we will compare the percentage of actions of type `navigate` (N), against the percentage of actions of type `acces` (A). We expect to see that N is grater for the dropout students, while A is greater non-dropout students.

%pyspark

# First we need to pivot the table to leave the labels as columns

train_logs_piv = train_logs.pivot_table(
    index=['course_id', 'event'], columns='label', values='eventRatio').rename(
    columns={0: 'NoDropout', 1: 'Dropout'}).reset_index()
train_logs_piv.loc[:, "Ratio difference"] = train_logs_piv.NoDropout - train_logs_piv.Dropout
train_logs_piv[:3]

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

g = seaborn.catplot(
    data=train_logs_piv, x="course_id", y="Ratio difference", hue='event',
    aspect=4, join=False, legend=False, dodge=True, kind='point',
    hue_order=['video', 'navigate', 'discussion', 'page_close', 'access', 'problem', 'wiki'],
    markers=['x', 'o', 'v', '^', '+', 'd', '1'])
handles = g._legend_data.values()
labels = g._legend_data.keys()
g.fig.legend(handles=handles, labels=labels, loc='upper center', ncol=4)
plt.plot([0, 38], [0, 0], linewidth=1, linestyle='-')
plt.ylim((-0.20, 0.20));

%md

As expected, there is a negative difference between the proportion of `navigate` events, and in a lesser extent of `access` and `page_close`, which indicates students that dropout are more likely to take this kind of actions. The opposite happens for `problem` and `discussion` events, being more common on students that do not drop out.

%md ## 2.3 Session analysis

To continue our analysis, we will split the data in sessions. Students interact with platforms in very different ways.

We define a session as a sequence of actions where the time between them does not exceed two hour limit. To create them, we use a window and a lag function.

Once we have applied the window, we can aggregate the data in sessions. For each of them we will include duration in minutes, start and end time, total actions, average and maximum number of minutes a student passed on each element of the session and count of event by type.

val sessions = actions.withColumn("newSession", (actions("minutesBetween") >= 120).cast("int"))
    .withColumn("sessionId", sum($"newSession").over(Window.partitionBy("enrollment_id")
    .orderBy("enrollment_id", "time", "prevAction")))
val aggEventCounts = sessions.na.fill(0).groupBy("enrollment_id", "sessionId")
    .pivot("event").count()

val aggSessions = sessions.na.fill(0).groupBy("enrollment_id", "sessionId").agg(
        count(lit(1)).alias("totalActions"), min("time").as("startTime"), max("time").as("endTime"),
        first("course_id").alias("course_id"),
        avg(when($"newSession" === 0 && $"minutesBetween" > 0, $"minutesBetween")).alias("avgMinutes"),
        max(when($"newSession" === 0, $"minutesBetween")).alias("maxMinutes"),
        max(when($"newSession" === 1, $"minutesBetween")).alias("minutesFromLastSession"))
    .join(aggEventCounts, Seq("enrollment_id", "sessionId"))
    .join(trainEnrollmentDF.select($"enrollment_id", $"label"), Seq("enrollment_id"))
    .orderBy("startTime").withColumn("duration", minutesBetween($"endTime", $"startTime"))
aggSessions.cache()
aggSessions.registerTempTable("aggSessions")
aggSessions.where($"enrollment_id" === 1).show()

## 2.4 Collecting sequences for Recurrent Neural Networks.

To use recurrent models, we need to convert each enrollment's interactions into a list of actions, using the `collect_list` aggregation function. Each enrollment will be represented by a string with all the object ids separated by a space, that can be later read as a sequence of text.

msg.data:
2.4 Collecting sequences for Recurrent Neural Networks.

To use recurrent models, we need to convert each enrollment’s interactions into a list of actions, using the collect_list aggregation function. Each enrollment will be represented by a string with all the object ids separated by a space, that can be later read as a sequence of text.

paragraphs.text:
val logSequences = trainLogsDF
    .select($"enrollment_id", concat($"object".cast("string"), lit("-"), $"event").as("object_info"))
    .orderBy("time")
    .groupBy("enrollment_id")
    .agg(collect_list($"object_info").as("object_sequence"))
    .join(trainEnrollmentDF.select($"enrollment_id", $"course_id".cast("int"), $"label"), Seq("enrollment_id"))

msg.data: logSequences: org.apache.spark.sql.DataFrame = [enrollment_id: int, object_sequence: array<string> ... 2 more fields]

paragraphs.text:
val sequenceList = udf((xs:Seq[String]) => xs match {
    case null => ""
    case _ => xs.mkString(" ")
})

logSequences
    .na.fill("")
    .withColumn("sequence", sequenceList($"object_sequence"))
    .drop("object_sequence")
    .write.format("com.databricks.spark.csv")
    .partitionBy("course_id")
    .mode(SaveMode.Overwrite)
    .option("header", "true")
    .save(new java.io.File(BASE_DATA_DIRNAME, "clean/train_sequences.csv").getPath)
